ummary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating metadata issues**\\n\\nI'm looking at whether an untracked metadata directory is preexisting, which we didn't create. It might be best not to edit the metadata and inspect if the file compiles without running it. There’s a potential problem with test coverage on line 207, particularly regarding the order of asserts in the class info test. Also, a concern arises with the Scala SAM for `SerializableStringSupplier` needing a method with parameters. Finally, I must consider how the native image might handle lambda class generation differently.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring lambda serialization issues**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how the dynamic-access class needs metadata for `Class#getDeclaredMethod` on lambda classes. This is self-testing, and I'm wondering if Forge manages the generated reachability metadata. Still, the lambda class might not be available until runtime, making serialized lambdas problematic. Native images support lambdas, but they may require reflection configuration. If the metadata captures the lambda class at the agent run, it might lose the same name in the native image build. Using an object with a `writeReplace` method could be a solution, even though it complicates things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing reflection and serialization**\\n\\nI'm considering how to cover reflection call sites and resources. It seems like I might need a private `writeReplace` method for this. The library sets accessibility to true, which could help. For the constructor, I’m looking at `new SerializedLambda(...)`, where I need to capture various arguments like the capturing class, functional interface class, method names, and signatures. I should gather all the required arguments to ensure everything works as expected when implementing this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating lambda image generation**\\n\\nI’m considering the native image generation for lambda functions and whether their metadata will be accessible. The `writeReplace` might work but could throw errors if it relies on private methods without registration. I’m also pondering if the class names of dynamically generated lambdas are stable after the compile order and how Graal handles lambda serialization. Perhaps I should search the repository for tests on serializable lambdas to clarify how they're treated.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_YNKlR3gtEr19kw4gNlHPso77|fc_0267f174ab6605d20169fb2037dda881a2a32df1a8a8f84794", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg \"SerializedLambda|Serializable.*Supplier|writeReplace|LineNumbers\" tests/src -g '*.scala' -g '*.java' | head -100"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"rg \\\"SerializedLambda|Serializable.*Supplier|writeReplace|LineNumbers\\\" tests/src -g '*.scala' -g '*.java' | head -100\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 370, "output": 941, "cacheRead": 25600, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 26911, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778065447728, "responseId": "resp_0267f174ab6605d20169fb20288f4081a29b787324c17e3e16"}}
